Exercise 13.9: What is a destructor? What does the synthesized destructor
do? When is a destructor synthesized?

Answer:
Destructor is a member function which starts with ~ and is called automatically when an object
is destroyed, if there is no destructor defined than the compiler creates a synthesized destructor
which is a destructor that has an empty body.

Exercise 13.10: What happens when a StrBlob object is destroyed? What
about a StrBlobPtr?

Answer:
StrBlob doesn't have a defined destructor so the compilers will create a synthesized one that only
implicity calls the destructor of shared_ptr that will check the ref count and if that reaches 0 will
call the destructor of vector.

StrBlobPtr doesn't have a defined destructor so the compilers will create a synthesized one that only
implicity calls the destructor of weak_ptr that doesn't free the memory of the vector.